Before we start, Let me explain some of the columns (features) as described by Kaggle.

  • Features V1, V2, … V28 are the principal components obtained with PCA (Principal Component Analysis), the only features which have not been transformed with PCA are 'Time' and 'Amount'.

  • Feature 'Time' contains the seconds elapsed between each transaction and the first transaction in the dataset.

  • feature 'Amount' is the transaction Amount, this feature can be used for example-dependant cost-sensitive learning.

  • Feature 'Class' is the response variable and it takes value 1 in case of fraud and 0 otherwise.

  • Given the high count of outliers across multiple columns, the Whisker’s Method is the most suitable approach for outlier removal.
In [8]:
cleaned_credit = credit.copy()
for column in cleaned_credit.columns:
    # Ignore class column
    if(column == "Class"):
        continue

    # Calculate Q1 and Q3 for Inter Quartile Range Calculation
    Q1 = credit[column].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = credit[column].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    
    # Define the bounds
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    # Replace outlier with mean 
    mean_replacer = credit[column].mean()
    to_replace = (cleaned_credit[column] < lower_bound) | (cleaned_credit[column] > upper_bound)
    cleaned_credit.loc[to_replace, column] = mean_replacer

  1. Evaluate the model's performance on the test set
In [22]:
y_pred = logreg.predict(X_test)

# Performance Metrics
metrics1 = {
    "Accuracy": accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred),
    "Precision": precision_score(y_test, y_pred),
    "Recall": recall_score(y_test, y_pred),
    "F1-Score": f1_score(y_test, y_pred)
}

for metric, value in metrics1.items():
    print(f"{metric}: {value:.4f}")

Accuracy: 0.9984
Precision: 0.8182
Recall: 0.0918
F1-Score: 0.1651

For this Logistic Regression model:

  • Accuracy (0.9984): High, but misleading due to class imbalance.
  • Precision (0.8182): Good, but still some false positives.
  • Recall (0.0918): Very low, missing most fraud cases.
  • F1-Score (0.1651): Poor balance, needs improvement in detecting fraud.
  1. Evaluating the performance of the logistic regression model using Log-Loss (Cross Entropy).
In [23]:
# Log-Loss Calculation
probs = logreg.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

log_loss_cal = -np.mean(y_test * np.log(probs) + (1 - y_test) * np.log(1 - probs))

print(f"Log Loss: {log_loss_cal}")

Log Loss: 0.009197601572482767

a. The log-loss was manually computed as 0.0092, indicating a low error in predicted probabilities.

b. A low log-loss indicates the model’s probability estimates are well-calibrated for the majority class (non-fraud). However, recall and F1-score show that fraud cases (which is the extremely large) are largely missed, meaning log-loss alone does not indicate effective fraud detection.

c. Log-loss considers probability confidence, meaning that even though accuracy is high, the model is overconfident in predicting the majority class (non-fraud). A low log-loss suggests well-calibrated probability estimates, but the poor recall means it still fails to capture fraud cases effectively. The model needs better handling of class imbalance to improve fraud detection.

  1. Plot the ROC Curve and print the AUC of the model on the test set
In [24]:
fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, probs)
roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='blue', label=f'Logistic Regression (AUC = {roc_auc:.4f})')
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='grey', linestyle='--')  
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate (Recall)')
plt.title('ROC Curve')
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.show()

print(f"AUC: {roc_auc:.4f}")

AUC: 0.8531

  • AUC-ROC (0.8531) indicates good but not excellent discrimination between fraud and non-fraud cases.

  • The model ranks fraud cases (Class = 1) higher than non-fraud cases 85.31% of the time, which is a decent performance.
